>
>	Wow! Quantum cryptosystems! When observed, they become stronger,
>probably the photons striking the algorithm has a tempering effect?
>
>	The correct statement is that a secure system's strength is
>independent of the secrecy of the details of the algorithm. If you have
>a secure system, and you have some other reason for keeping the details
>to yourself, this doesn't make the system more breakable.
>
>	Please don't give me some jive about how the NSA can't know
>it's secure unless they post it here so every ignorant goober can
>peer at it. This is like saying 'we can't be *sure* Ali was *really*
>a great boxer, after all, he never fought Pee Wee Herman!'
>
>	All this is, of course, almost completely independent of
>the actual security of Clipper.
>
>	Dr. Andrew Molitor
>	Dept. Of Mathematical Sciences
>	NMSU
